Eternal Beef Community Collective – 501(c)(3) Proposal
 
MISSION STATEMENT
The Eternal Beef Community Collective is dedicated to fostering healthy, creative, and supportive communities through skateboarding, cycling, arts education, and mutual aid. We provide free or low-cost lessons, workshops, community service initiatives, and collaborative creative opportunities for youth, artists, and underserved residents.
 
VISION
We envision a Bay Area where every young person—regardless of financial background—has access to:
- Skateboarding instruction
- Creative expression
- Safe communal spaces
- Transportation empowerment
- Community belonging
 
CORE PROGRAMS
A. Skate Lessons & Art Classes
- Free or sliding-scale skateboarding lessons
- Art classes taught by local artists
- Youth mentorship
- Safety equipment library
- Creative workshops
 
B. Bike Program / Group Ride Club
- Group rides
- Bike maintenance days
- Mechanical skills workshops
- Advocacy for safe streets
 
C. Skate Houses (Communal Resource Hubs)
- Lending libraries
- Communal meals
- Workshops
- Safe base for youth
 
D. Community Services
- Cleanup days
- Mutual aid distribution
- Youth volunteer opportunities
- Partnerships with local orgs
 
E. “Yamo Interviews” Media Project
A filmed interview series highlighting community members, artists, skaters, and activists.
 
TARGET POPULATION
Youth 12–25, underserved SF neighborhoods, housing-insecure youth, and new/beginner skaters and cyclists.
 
PUBLIC BENEFIT
We provide free educational programming, reduce barriers to recreation, promote mental health, improve public spaces, and support youth development.
 
ORGANIZATIONAL STRUCTURE
Board of Directors (Executive Director, Treasurer, Secretary) and volunteer teams including skate instructors, bike mechanics, artists, outreach, and media crews.
 
PROJECTED YEAR 1 BUDGET
Insurance: $2,500
Skate Equipment: $4,000
Bike Tools/Parts: $3,500
Art Supplies: $2,000
Media Gear: $1,500
Permits/Venue: $4,000
Meals for Interviews: $1,200
Marketing: $800
Admin Fees: $1,500
Total: ~$21,000
 
FUNDING STRATEGY
A. Grants: Tony Hawk Foundation, Surdna, SF Grants for the Arts, REI, Borealis, CBDs.
B. Sponsorships: Skate brands, bike shops, local restaurants.
C. Community Funding: Patreon, merch, fundraiser events, donation jars.
 
COMPLIANCE CHECKLIST
Articles of Incorporation, Nonprofit Bylaws, Conflict of Interest Policy, Public Benefit Statement, Board Roster, 1023-EZ Application, Activity Descriptions, Budget, Program Descriptions, Fundraising Plan.